Answer: My Model is based on Convolutional Neural Network

What is a Convolutional Network Networks (CNN)

A Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) is comprised of one or more convolutional layers (often with a subsampling step) and then followed by one or more fully connected layers as in a standard multilayer neural network. The architecture of a CNN is designed to take advantage of the 2D structure of an input image (or other 2D input such as a speech signal). This is achieved with local connections and tied weights followed by some form of pooling which results in translation invariant features. Another benefit of CNNs is that they are easier to train and have many fewer parameters than fully connected networks with the same number of hidden units. In this article we will discuss the architecture of a CNN and the back propagation algorithm to compute the gradient with respect to the parameters of the model in order to use gradient based optimization.

Question 2¶

What does your final architecture look like? (Type of model, layers, sizes, connectivity, etc.)

Answer: Final Model Contains 6 layers.

  • 3 Convolutional Layer

    • First Convolutional layer with depth 12

      • ReLU
      • Stride of 1 x 1
      • input 32 x 32 x 1
      • output 32 x 32 x 6

    • Second Convolutional layer with depth 24

      • ReLU
      • Stride of 2 x 2
      • input 32 x 32 x 6
      • output 16 x 16 x 12

    • Third Convolutional layer with deth 36

      • ReLU
      • Stride of 2 x 2
      • input 16 x 16 x 12
      • output 8 x 8 x 24

  • 2 Fully Connected Layer

    • 1st Layer

      • Reshaped to 1 dimension with 8 8 24 features
      • 300 Neurons
      • ReLU

    • 2nd Layer

      • 200 Neurons
      • ReLU
      • Dropout with keeping probablity -> pkeep
  • Output Layer
    • Will contain 5 different classifiers on top
    • Each classifier
      • Different Weight and Biases
      • Ylogit = tf.matmul(Dropout, W) + B
      • Output = softmax(Ylogit)

Step 2: Train a Model on a Realistic Dataset¶

Once you have settled on a good architecture, you can train your model on real data. In particular, the Street View House Numbers (SVHN) dataset is a good large-scale dataset collected from house numbers in Google Street View. Training on this more challenging dataset, where the digits are not neatly lined-up and have various skews, fonts and colors, likely means you have to do some hyperparameter exploration to perform well.

Question 5¶

What changes did you have to make, if any, to achieve "good" results? Were there any options you explored that made the results worse?

Answer:

  • Resized all the images to 32 x 96 (more width should give CNN a better result)
  • Made Convolution Layers twice as deep from my initial condition
  • Added an extra fully connected layers containing 300 neurons
  • Decreased learning rate from 0.01 to 0.005
  • Increased Exponential decay rate to make learning rate daecy faster
  • Rolled over the data 25 times (25 epochs)

All these changes gave me nearly 3 % Boost from my initial results¶
